The article discusses the devastating impact of sexual assault and emphasizes the need for everyone to stand up against it. It acknowledges that the COVID-19 pandemic has made it more challenging for survivors to seek help and for service providers to offer support. The article also highlights that sexual assault was already a public health crisis prior to the pandemic, with one in five women being victims of completed or attempted rape. The Biden administration is committed to addressing this crisis and has allocated $450 million in supplemental funding for domestic violence and sexual assault services. They have also established the White House Gender Policy Council and an independent review commission to improve the response to sexual assault and harassment. The article calls for the renewal and improvement of the Violence Against Women Act (VAWA) and praises the recent passing of the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2021 by the House of Representatives. It concludes by urging individuals, organizations, and institutions to come together and commit to being part of the solution in creating a society where sexual violence is not tolerated and survivors are supported.